Leading brain specialists have signed up to help  improve safety for fighters in Britain in the aftermath of the death of boxer  Bradley Stone.
A working party of neurologists and neuro-surgeons will study the whole  question of head injuries in the ring under the chairmanship of consultant Mr  Peter Richards from Charing Cross Hospital, London.
And the general secretary of the British Boxing Board of Control, John  Morris, said several "eminent people" had attended a meeting on Tuesday which  had "already led to positive steps".
Stone, 20, died after his British super-bantamweight title contest in  London last month. Recommendations will be considered by board doctors from  all parts of Britain in July.
